# Bonus Challenge: Full Environment

Objective: compose networking, VM deployment, and patch management into one parameterized Azure environment using reusable Terraform modules.

## Project Structure
```
modules/
  vnet/                # Virtual Network + Subnet module
  nsg/                 # Network Security Group module
  vm/                  # Linux VM with NGINX + public IP
  log_analytics/       # Log Analytics Workspace module
  automation_account/  # Automation Account module
  update_management/   # Update Management module
main.tf                # Root configuration to call modules
variables.tf           # Input variables
terraform.tfvars       # Variable values
output.tf              # Output public IPs and VM IDs
README                 # This documentation
provider.tf            # Azure provider configuration
```

## Modules Overview

### vnet/
Creates a virtual network and one or more subnets.

### nsg/
Creates a Network Security Group. Inbound ports such as 22 (SSH) and 80 (HTTP) are controlled through `nsg_security_rules` in `terraform.tfvars`.

### vm/
Deploys one or more Linux VMs using `for_each`, installs NGINX using cloud-init, and associates the NSG.

### log_analytics/
Creates a Log Analytics Workspace to collect logs and monitor update compliance.

### automation_account/
Creates an Azure Automation Account and links it to the Log Analytics Workspace.

### update_management/
Registers the deployed VMs for patching and schedules a weekly patch deployment.

## Architecture Diagram

```
Internet
    |
    v
[ NSG ] -- inbound 22, 80
    |
    v
[ Linux VM(s) with NGINX ] <-- Update Management (weekly patches)
    |
    v
[ VNET + Subnet(s) ]

[ Automation Account ] --> [ Update Management ] --> [ VM(s) ]
[ Log Analytics Workspace ]
```

## Usage Guide

1. Configure `terraform.tfvars`:
   - set `location`, `tags`, and `schedule_start_time`
   - define `nsg_security_rules` for ports 22 and 80
   - define one or more VMs in the `vms` map

2. Initialize and deploy:
   ```
   terraform init
   terraform plan
   terraform apply
   ```

3. Access the web server using the output public IP on port 80.

    

4. Monitor patches via Azure Portal > Automation Account > Update Management.

## Running Independently

The Bonus Challenge is a **self-contained, standalone deployment**. It does NOT depend on Assignment 1 or Assignment 2 being deployed first. It creates its own resource group, networking, VMs, and patch management from scratch using the same shared modules.

To run it independently:
```
cd env/bonuschallenge
terraform init
terraform plan
terraform apply
```

No prior state from other assignments is needed.

## Important: Deprecation Notice
> **Azure Automation Update Management was deprecated on 31st August 2024 and has been shut down on 28th February 2025.**
> Microsoft recommends migrating to **Azure Update Manager**.
> Learn more: https://aka.ms/mmaagentbasedservicesshutdown
>
> This configuration uses `azurerm_automation_software_update_configuration` for demonstration purposes. In production, use Azure Update Manager (`azurerm_maintenance_configuration`) instead.


